  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under U.S. federal law, money laundering can result in significant criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Potential Criminal Penalties:\n- Imprisonment of up to 20 years\n- Substantial financial fines\n- Potential asset forfeiture\n- Criminal record\n\n2. Financial Penalties:\n- Fines can be up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction\n\n3. Additional Consequences:\n- Potential civil penalties\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Difficulty obtaining future employment\n- Immigration consequences for non-citizens\n\nThe specific penalties depend on factors like transaction amount, prior criminal history, and specific circumstances of the offense. Penalties can be more severe if the laundering involves larger amounts or is connected to other serious crimes like drug trafficking.\n\nThese details are based on general federal statutes, particularly the Money Laundering Control Act. For precise legal advice about a specific situation, consulting a qualified criminal defense attorney is recommended.",
